/*
 * CEF OSR spike (spike/cef-osr).
 *
 * The polyui executable statically links its own SQLite (sqlx ->
 * libsqlite3-sys) and, separately, loads the system libsqlite3.so.0 that
 * WebKitGTK depends on. Rust exports the bundled sqlite3_* symbols from the
 * executable, and in ELF the executable is first in the global lookup scope,
 * so it interposes over the shared library for every consumer in the process.
 *
 * Worse, only the ~51 symbols sqlx actually calls survive into the binary, so
 * the interposition is *partial*: some of libsqlite3.so's internal calls bind
 * to the bundled copy while the rest stay in the .so. State built by one copy
 * gets handed to the other.
 *
 * Nothing exercised that path until CEF arrived: CEF's network stack
 * initializes NSS, NSS loads libsoftokn3.so, softokn3 drives libsqlite3 -- and
 * it dies on a null function pointer inside NSS_InitReadWrite.
 *
 * Hiding the bundled symbols makes them local to the executable. Rust's own
 * calls into them are statically bound and unaffected; nothing outside needs
 * to resolve sqlite3_* against the executable.
 */
{
  local:
    sqlite3_*;
};
